\label{lemma:delete_edges}
Let $\cG \coloneqq (X, R)$ be a Borel graph with $\deg(\cG) < \infty$. Suppose that for each $r > 0$ there is a symmetric Borel subset $Q \subseteq R$ such that
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \label{item1:delete_edges} $\rho_\cG(x_0, x_1) > r$ whenever $x_0, x_1 \in X$ and there are two distinct $q_0, q_1 \in Q$ such that $x_i$ is adjacent to $q_i$, for $i = 0,1$,
    \item \label{item2:delete_edges} the graph $\cG_0 \coloneqq (X, R \setminus Q)$ admits a Borel orientation with out-degree at most 1.
\end{enumerate}
Then $\asdim (X,\rho_\cG) \le 3$.

nodes.proof:
Fix $r > 0$. We aim to build a $\rho_\cG$-uniformly bounded Borel equivalence relation $E \subseteq E_\cG$ such that $B_{\rho_\cG}(x, r)$ intersects at most four $E$-classes, for every $x \in X$. To do so, let $Q \subseteq R$ be satisfying the assumptions of the lemma for $2r$, so in particular, given $x_0, x_1 \in X$
\begin{equation} \label{eq:2r}
\text{ $\rho_\cG(x_0, x_1) > 2r$ if there are $q_0, q_1 \in Q$, $q_0 \ne q_1$ and $x_i$ is adjacent to $q_i$, for $i = 0,1$.} \tag{1'}
\end{equation}

Consider $\cG_0 \coloneqq (X, R \setminus Q)$. By \eqref{item2:delete_edges} and Proposition \ref{prop:oriented} we have $\asdim (X,\rho_{\cG_0}) \le 1$, which means that there is a $\rho_{\cG_0}$-uniformly bounded (and thus $\rho_\cG$-uniformly bounded) Borel equivalence relation $E$ such that for every $x \in X$ the ball $B_{\rho_{\cG_0}}(x, 2r)$ intersects at most two distinct $E$-classes. We claim that, for every $x \in X$, the ball $B_{\rho_\cG}(x, r)$ intersects at most 4 $E$-classes.

To see this, let $Y \subseteq X$ be the set of all vertices that are adjacent to some edge in $Q$. Fix $x \in X$. If $B_{\rho_{\cG}}(x, r) \cap Y = \emptyset$, then 
\begin{equation*}
B_{\rho_{\cG}}(x, r) = B_{\rho_{\cG_0}}(x, r) \subseteq B_{\rho_{\cG_0}}(x, 2r)
\end{equation*}
and thus $B_{\rho_{\cG}}(x, r)$ intersects at most two $E$-classes.

Suppose next that $B_{\rho_{\cG}}(x, r) \cap Y \ne \emptyset$. Then by \eqref{eq:2r} there is  (up to symmetry) a unique edge $ (y, z) \in Q$ such that at least one among $y$ and $z$ belongs to  $B_{\rho_{\cG}}(x, r)$. Without loss of generality, we may assume $y \in B_{\rho_{\cG}}(x, r)$. In this case, again by \eqref{eq:2r}, we have 
\[
B_{\rho_{\cG}}(x, r) \subseteq B_{\rho_{\cG}}(y, 2r) \subseteq B_{\rho_{\cG_0}}(y, 2r) \cup B_{\rho_{\cG_0}}(z, 2r).
\]
We deduce that $B_{\rho_{\cG}}(x, r)$ intersects at most 4 different $E$-classes.

Note that $Y$ is Borel by Remark \ref{remark:degree_maps}. We can therefore define a Borel graph $(R|_Y, S)$ as follows: given two distinct $q_0, q_1 \in R|_Y$, we write $q_0 S q_1$ if there are vertices $x_0, x_1 \in Y$ such that $x_i$ is $R$-adjacent to $q_i$ for $i= 0,1$ and $\rho_\cG(x_0, x_1) \le r$. The graph $(R|_Y, S)$ has finite degree since $\cG$ does, hence by \cite[Propositions 4.2 and 4.3]{KST} there exists a maximal \emph{$S$-independent} Borel set $Q_0 \subseteq R|_Y$, that is
\begin{equation} \label{eq:S-indep}
q_0 \neg S q_1 \text{ for all } q_0, q_1 \in Q_0 \text{ and every } q \in R|_Y \text{ is $S$-adjacent to some element of $Q_0$}.
\end{equation}

Consider next the Borel set
\begin{equation*}
Q \coloneqq \{ (x,y) \in Q_0 \cup Q_0^{-1} : \min \{ \rho_\cG(x, \leaves(\cG)), \rho_\cG(y, \leaves(\cG)) \} \ge r \}.
\end{equation*}
We have that $Q$ satisfies condition \eqref{item1:choose_edges} by \eqref{eq:S-indep}, and \eqref{item2:choose_edges} by definition. We verify \eqref{item3:choose_edges} for $x \in Y$, since the conclusion is automatic for $x \in X \setminus Y$.

Set $\cG_0 \coloneqq (X, R \setminus Q)$.  Note first that, by construction, we have $|[x ]_{\cG_0}| < \infty$, hence the latter (if non-trivial) is a finite graph of degree at most 2 with two leaves, say $x_0$ and $x_1$. We moreover point out that $\rho_\cG(y, z) = \rho_{\cG_0}(y,z)$ for every $y,z \in [x]_{\cG_0}$, as $\cG$ is acyclic.

Since $\deg(\cG) \le 2$, for every $y \in [x]_{\cG_0} \setminus \{x_0, x_1\}$, the only two vertices in $\cG$ that are $R$-adjacent  to $y$ are necessarily in $[x]_{\cG_0}$. This implies
\begin{equation} \label{eq:distance}
\rho_\cG(y,z) = \min \{ \rho_\cG(y,x_0) + \rho_\cG(x_0,z),  \rho_\cG(y,x_1) + \rho_\cG(x_1,z) \}, \quad y \in [x]_{\cG_0}, \, z \notin [x]_{\cG_0}.
\end{equation}

There are thus two cases: the first one is that $[x]_{\cG_0}$ contains no edge from $Q_0$. In this case, by \eqref{eq:S-indep} and \eqref{eq:distance}, we necessarily have that each $y \in [x]_{\cG_0}$ has distance at most $r$ from either $x_0$ or $x_1$, and therefore
\begin{equation*}
|[x]_{\cG_0}| \le \rho_{\cG_0}(x_0, x_1) + 1 \le 2r +2.
\end{equation*}

On the other hand, suppose that some edges in $Q_0 \setminus Q$ occur in $[x]_{\cG_0}$. This can only happen if at least one among $x_0$ and $x_1$ belongs to $\leaves(\cG)$. Note that there can be at most two edges  in $Q_0 \setminus Q$ appearing in $[x]_{\cG_0}$, as a third one would necessarily belong to $Q$ by construction. By \eqref{eq:S-indep}, all possible scenarios are in the pictures below.







